You're like, oh, I'm cheating.

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:04.000
No, no.

00:04:04.300 --> 00:04:05.920
I mean, a little, I guess.

00:04:06.100 --> 00:04:09.660
But, you know, it's the thing like everyone else used PyTorch

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:12.660
and we had just started working on TensorFlow too

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:14.780
when I joined whereas PyTorch had already been mature.

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:17.440
So it was the responsible thing to do.

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:18.880
I think.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:21.720
And Transformers.

00:04:22.360 --> 00:04:23.240
What are these Transformer things?

00:04:24.020 --> 00:04:25.040
They came out of Google, right?

00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:27.960
Yeah, yeah, they did. Attention is all you need.

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:35.080
These Transformer things, I guess, are the backbone of all these large language models that we're seeing today.

00:04:35.660 --> 00:04:45.900
And they've proved to have an incredible capacity for modeling, I guess, in a generative way, all kinds of text.

00:04:46.020 --> 00:04:55.440
And in a way that, honestly, if I had to admit, like surprised me, like at the time in 27 to 18, like we were doing good work in like machine translation and stuff.

00:04:56.540 --> 00:05:07.100
But even back then, you know, there was researchers who were working on at Google Brain, like, you know, code generation, like writing a bunch of unit tests, stuff that people do regularly today, actually, with large language models.

00:05:08.860 --> 00:05:13.260
I was I put on my systems engineer hat back then, and I was a little skeptical, to be honest.

00:05:13.840 --> 00:05:16.420
have just totally proved wrong and I'm happy to have been proved wrong.

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:20.340
So it's been phenomenal seeing sort of that,

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:25.840
the success of that particular model. And yeah,

00:05:26.120 --> 00:05:27.820
having played a very small part in it.

00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:28.860
Yeah. I was,

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:33.160
I've been a long time skeptic of machine learning in the sense that for so

00:05:33.340 --> 00:05:37.980
long, it was, it's kind of like fusion. It's, it's going to be amazing,

00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:41.460
but it's 10, 20, 30 years out and, and maybe, you know,

00:05:42.020 --> 00:05:48.340
And it was all almost like knowledge, knowledge-based type things.

00:05:48.490 --> 00:05:51.380
And just, I mean, it was interesting.

00:05:51.490 --> 00:05:55.840
It looked kind of relevant and possibly useful in some of the cases, but not like it is today.

00:05:56.180 --> 00:06:02.240
Like today, people don't even care about technology, are blown away by this stuff.

00:06:02.240 --> 00:06:03.240
And they use it all day long.

00:06:03.370 --> 00:06:08.640
And it's gone so much farther and so much faster than I expected it to.

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:12.060
I'm all about it these days.

