guys perceive the need for the scale of the computation?

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:52.220
Like, you know, to train GPT-01, I don't know how much compute was involved, but probably

00:09:52.350 --> 00:09:55.680
more than cities use in terms of energy sometimes, you know what I mean?

00:09:56.230 --> 00:09:56.900
It was a lot.

00:09:57.580 --> 00:10:02.380
And how much compute were you all using back then versus now,

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:04.520
I guess is what I'm getting at.

00:10:04.960 --> 00:10:07.120
So I guess, yeah, and I think you kind of said it,

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:11.720
but just to clarify or to make it clear that I personally didn't work on

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:14.460
Transformers. I was working on TensorFlow. So the, yeah, the,

00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:20.520
I guess embedded DSL for training machine learning models that was used within

00:10:20.720 --> 00:10:21.660
Google and still used today.

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:25.780
I can't give you specific numbers to be honest,

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:36.600
Because I was pretty deep in the systems part of working on TensorFlow and not paying too much attention for standing up distributed clusters.

00:10:37.860 --> 00:10:43.600
I did things like adding support to TensorFlow for creating a function library.

00:10:45.080 --> 00:10:48.480
TensorFlow is like a Dataflow graph engine, and it didn't have functions in it.

00:10:48.480 --> 00:10:51.860
So I added support for functions, partitioning functions over devices.

00:10:52.660 --> 00:10:55.860
But other teams used that work to go and train the big models.

00:10:56.520 --> 00:11:03.400
I know it was a lot of compute, but a lot versus a lot, you know, all caps versus, you know, just capital case.

00:11:04.680 --> 00:11:05.860
Yeah, I'm sure there's a delta.

00:11:05.930 --> 00:11:07.440
I just, I don't know how much.

00:11:07.640 --> 00:11:07.880
Yeah.

00:11:08.550 --> 00:11:14.000
Well, today they're all talking about restarting nuclear reactors and plugging them straight to the data center.

00:11:14.200 --> 00:11:15.280
So it's a weird time.

00:11:16.980 --> 00:11:20.060
Let's go back maybe a little bit before then.

00:11:21.360 --> 00:11:25.040
2012 or so, I believe is maybe the right time frame.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:27.040
I mean, let's talk about notebooks.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.380
And around then, Jupyter Notebooks burst on the scene.

00:11:32.990 --> 00:11:38.260
And I think they fundamentally changed the ecosystem of Python

00:11:40.940 --> 00:11:44.300
and basically scientific work in general.

00:11:46.880 --> 00:11:50.600
By changing Python, I mean there are so many people in Python

00:11:50.730 --> 00:11:53.880
who are here because they got pulled into a notebook.

00:11:54.580 --> 00:11:55.680
They wrote a little bit of code.

00:11:56.050 --> 00:11:57.100
They got incredible results.

00:11:58.360 --> 00:11:59.880
They were never, ever a programmer,

00:11:59.970 --> 00:12:01.980
but now they're the maintainer of an open source project

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:02.980
or something like that.

00:12:03.420 --> 00:12:03.940
You know what I mean?

00:12:04.540 --> 00:12:06.940
They're just like, oh, this is kind of neat.

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:09.660
Oh, I'll create a biology library or whatever.

00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:14.740
And then all of a sudden, they're deep in it.

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:19.020
And so, Jupyter, I think, was really the start of that.

00:12:19.140 --> 00:12:21.700
Maybe there was some precursors that I'm not familiar with.

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:26.360
Yeah, Jupyter was essentially the start of it, especially for Python.

00:12:26.650 --> 00:12:29.640
Like, I think the idea of computation on notebooks has been around.

00:12:30.330 --> 00:12:36.900
But, yeah, the IPython REPL, I guess the IPython project with the IPython REPL, I think, was early 2000s.

00:12:38.259 --> 00:12:49.800
And Jupyter, I think you're right, like 2012-ish, as he's burst onto the scene with putting the IPython REPL into a web browser with multiple REPL cells.

00:12:50.160 --> 00:12:54.440
And all of a sudden you could do more than what you could do in the console and also made it a lot more accessible.

00:12:55.720 --> 00:12:55.800
Yeah.

00:12:57.040 --> 00:13:06.120
Going back to that sixth cell you entered on your REPL and editing it, that is not a way to draw beginners in.

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:08.420
No, definitely not.

00:13:08.920 --> 00:13:10.240
Up arrow key six times, no.

00:13:10.700 --> 00:13:16.720
Yeah, 2012 coincidentally is when I started college as an undergrad.

00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:24.660
So I had been using, I kind of grew up, as long as I used Python, I think I probably was using Jupyter Notebooks.

00:13:24.900 --> 00:13:31.280
And I even started using Google Colab before it was made public, because when I was interning at Google.

00:13:31.340 --> 00:13:37.260
And I think the year I started working at Google full-time is when they made it public to the world.

00:13:37.700 --> 00:13:43.600
So yeah, Notebooks have sort of shaped the way that I think and interact with code quite a bit.

00:13:44.980 --> 00:13:45.900
Yeah, absolutely.

00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:51.820
So maybe you could give us some perspective.

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:54.220
It sounds like you were there right at the right time.

00:13:55.800 --> 00:14:00.820
What was the goal and sort of the job of Jupyter Notebooks

00:14:00.860 --> 00:14:02.120
and those kinds of things then?

00:14:03.260 --> 00:14:05.260
And how has that changed now?

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:07.660
And maybe how does it still solve that problem

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:08.880
or not solve it so much?

00:14:10.160 --> 00:14:14.500
Yeah, I think, so stepping back,

00:14:14.660 --> 00:14:22.540
So you mentioned how many people who might not have traditionally worked with code sort

00:14:22.540 --> 00:14:24.440
of came into it because of Jupyter Notebooks.

00:14:24.450 --> 00:14:25.820
And I think that's really...

00:14:26.860 --> 00:14:27.900
I think you're onto something there.

00:14:27.900 --> 00:14:28.540
I think that's correct.

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:37.260
And I think the special thing about Notebooks is that they mix code and visuals and narrative

00:14:37.500 --> 00:14:40.020
text in this interactive programming environment.

00:14:40.980 --> 00:14:46.240
And that interactivity in particular, I think, is really important for anyone who works with data.

00:14:47.680 --> 00:15:00.820
It's where you got to like first like, you know, run some queries against your data to see the general shape of it, you know, run some transformations to see like, you know, basically like explore your data, like hold it in your hands, right?

00:15:00.910 --> 00:15:09.700
And like, you know, repls before and then Jupyter Notebooks in particular lets you do that in a way that you just can't easily do in a script because it holds the variables in memory.

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:20.680
And so I think the role that it played was that it enabled data scientists or computational scientists, biologists, astrophysicists, all these different types of people who work with data.

00:15:22.680 --> 00:15:33.920
It let them rapidly experiment with code and models and importantly get some kind of like artifact out of it.

00:15:34.180 --> 00:15:41.840
And in particular, this was like a static HTML type artifact, right, where you have some text documenting what experiments you're running.

00:15:42.600 --> 00:15:47.640
You have Python code, and then you have like matplotlib plots and other artifacts.

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:57.900
And I think for the sciences in particular early on, that was super important and transformative.

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:01.440
And we were talking about other computational notebook environments.

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:08.980
And it's interesting to mention this because things like this existed before Mathematica's workbooks, I think they called them.

00:16:08.980 --> 00:16:10.000
