00:27:19.880 --> 00:27:23.080
So Marimo is an open source notebook for Python.

00:27:23.970 --> 00:27:29.880
The main thing that's different between Marimo and Jupyter is that Marimo is reactive.

00:27:30.530 --> 00:27:38.160
And what that means is that unlike a Jupyter notebook where you can run cells in any arbitrary order you like,

00:27:39.060 --> 00:27:49.380
In Marimo, when you run one cell, it knows what other cells need to be run in order to make sure that your code and outputs are synchronized.

00:27:49.800 --> 00:27:51.120
So it's kind of like Excel, right?

00:27:51.180 --> 00:27:52.420
So you have two cells.

00:27:52.720 --> 00:27:53.460
One declares X.

00:27:53.840 --> 00:27:54.840
Another one references X.

00:27:55.280 --> 00:27:57.580
You run the cell that declares X or defines X.

00:27:58.940 --> 00:28:03.840
All other cells that reference X will automatically run or they'll be marked as stale.

00:28:03.940 --> 00:28:07.140
You can configure it if you're scared of automatic execution.

00:28:07.840 --> 00:28:12.620
But the point is that it manages your variables for you

00:28:13.120 --> 00:28:15.960
so that you don't have to worry about outputs

00:28:16.280 --> 00:28:18.240
becoming decohered from your code.

00:28:18.580 --> 00:28:20.340
And similarly, if you delete a cell,

00:28:22.280 --> 00:28:23.780
the variable will be scrubbed from memory

00:28:23.990 --> 00:28:25.500
and then cells that depended on it

00:28:25.620 --> 00:28:27.640
will either be marked as stale with a big warning

00:28:27.920 --> 00:28:29.740
or automatically run and invalidated.

00:28:30.700 --> 00:28:34.140
So that reactivity provides some amount of reproducibility.

00:28:36.080 --> 00:28:37.720
And then it also-- some other key features,

00:28:37.780 --> 00:28:39.640
and then we can dive into each of them,

00:28:39.840 --> 00:28:41.980
is an additional reactivity.

00:28:42.560 --> 00:28:44.540
Marima notebooks are stored as pure Python files,

00:28:44.820 --> 00:28:47.340
which makes them easy to version with Git.

